'''''ShCh-214''''' was a [[Shchuka-class submarine|''Shchuka''-class submarine]] of the [[Soviet Navy]]. Her keel was laid down by 61 Kommunara in Nikolajev on 13 July 1935. She was launched on 23 April 1937 and commissioned on 4 March 1939 in the [[Black Sea Fleet]].
Submarine was under command of Captain Vlasov Vladimir Yakovlevich until the loss of the vessel.<ref>{{cite web |author=Orlov Alex, Dmitriy Metelev, Evgeniy Chirva |url=http://www.town.ural.ru/ship/means/mens_v.php3#vlasov |title=<U+0412><U+0435><U+043B><U+0438><U+043A><U+0430><U+044F> <U+041E><U+0442><U+0435><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+0435><U+043D><U+043D><U+0430><U+044F> - <U+043F><U+043E><U+0434> <U+0432><U+043E><U+0434><U+043E><U+0439> |publisher=Town.ural.ru |date= |accessdate=2014-08-26}}</ref>

==Loss==
After having performed attacks in southern Black Sea, the submarine was employed as a transport unit to support the Soviet forces in the [[Siege of Sevastopol (1941<U+2013>42)|Siege of Sevastopol]]. During one of these mission, ShCh-214 was torpedoed in surface by the Italian motor torpedo boat MAS-571. 2 men of the crew survived.

==Service history==
Submarine scored some sinking in southern Black Sea, often against neutral Turkish schooners.

